{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 10: Performance Measurement and Investment Decisions\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 10 delves into the methodologies and metrics used for performance measurement and investment decisions, focusing on key concepts such as Return on Investment (ROI), Residual Income (RI), and the Balanced Scorecard. The chapter explains various formulas for calculating ROI and RI, and discusses their advantages and disadvantages. It also covers non-financial performance indicators and their role in comprehensive performance assessment. The chapter includes practical examples and quizzes to illustrate the application of these concepts in real-world scenarios, such as evaluating divisional performance and making investment decisions.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The chapter is highly significant due to its comprehensive coverage of essential performance measurement and investment decision-making tools.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Return on Investment (ROI) is a versatile and widely used performance metric.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Return on Investment (ROI) is a measure used to evaluate the efficiency and profitability of an investment or the performance of a division by comparing income with the operational assets used to generate that income. It can be calculated in several ways, such as ROI = (Controllable profit / Total net assets) * 100 or ROI = Operating profit / Capital employed. These formulas highlight that ROI can be expressed as a percentage and is used to determine the target profit in target costing. For example, Division A has an ROI of 15.08%, and Division B has an ROI of 17.72% [Data: Concepts (204, 1177); Relationships (262, 190)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Residual Income (RI) provides a different perspective on profitability.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Residual Income (RI) is the amount of income that an individual or company has after all expenses have been paid. It is calculated by subtracting the imputed interest charge from the net profit. RI serves as a measure of the profitability of an investment after accounting for the cost of capital. For instance, Division A has a Residual Income of $2.552 million, while Division B has a Residual Income of $2.322 million. This metric focuses on wealth creation by deducting an imputed interest expense from the pre-tax profit [Data: Concepts (1174, 1184); Relationships (1166, 1161)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The Balanced Scorecard integrates financial and non-financial performance indicators.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Balanced Scorecard is a strategic planning and management system used to align business activities to the vision and strategy of the organization. It improves internal and external communications and monitors organizational performance against strategic goals. The case of Performance Measurement and Investment Decisions: Implementing the Balanced Scorecard and Residual Income Approaches illustrates the use of the Balanced Scorecard in evaluating the performance of two divisions, highlighting the integration of financial metrics like ROI and RI with non-financial performance indicators [Data: Concepts (2275, 1509); Relationships (1092, 264)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Non-financial performance indicators are crucial for a holistic performance assessment.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Non-financial performance indicators are metrics used to assess various aspects of a company's performance that are not directly related to financial outcomes. These indicators encompass areas such as quality, customer satisfaction, employee engagement, and operational efficiency, which can lead to better long-term performance. Examples include customer satisfaction, employee turnover, and operational efficiency. These indicators complement financial performance measures and help avoid excessive cost-cutting that may harm the business [Data: Concepts (1509, 1086); Relationships (1442, 1438)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Quizzes and practical examples enhance understanding of performance metrics.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes several quizzes and practical examples to illustrate the application of performance metrics in real-world scenarios. For instance, the quiz on ROI vs. Residual Income compares the decision-making process using ROI and RI for a project with a projected ROI of 21.5%. Another quiz involves calculating the current ROI and residual income for Division X and showing how they would change under two proposals. These practical exercises help reinforce the theoretical concepts and demonstrate their relevance in business decision-making [Data: Concepts (1537, 1176); Relationships (1169, 1163)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Advantages and disadvantages of ROI and RI are discussed in detail.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter provides a comprehensive discussion on the advantages and disadvantages of ROI and RI. Advantages of ROI include ease of comparison between divisions, focus on scarce capital resources, and easily understood percentages. However, it also has disadvantages such as the risk of dysfunctional decision-making and the potential for window-dressing. On the other hand, residual income overcomes some of the problems associated with ROI, such as dysfunctional behavior and holding on to old assets, but it is less easily understood than a percentage and can be affected by the definition of capital employed [Data: Concepts (1172, 1182); Relationships (1159, 1183)].\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery within a textbook. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., concepts, methodologies, quizzes, examples, cases) within a chapter of a textbook.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a chapter, given a list of concepts, methodologies, formulas and examples that belong to the chapter as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform educators and students about the chapter's content and its key components. The content of this report includes an overview of the chapter's key entities, their definitions, interrelations, and noteworthy details.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: Chapter title - the title is given in the textbook in the format 'Chapter X: title'\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary that outlines the chapter's structure and the main learning outcomes. Focus on the key concepts as mentioned in the learning outcomes, their relevant examples, formulas, and methodologies, and how these elements are related to each other.\n- IMPACT SEVERITY RATING: a float score between 0-10 that represents the significance of the chapter's content. This score reflects the importance and relevance of the chapter's material in the context of the textbook.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the significance rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the chapter. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format:\n    {{\n        \"title\": <report_title>,\n        \"summary\": <executive_summary>,\n        \"rating\": <impact_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": <rating_explanation>,\n        \"findings\": [\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_1_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_1_explanation>\n            }},\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_2_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n204,\"\"\"RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI)\"\"\",\"Return on Investment (ROI) is a measure used to evaluate the efficiency and profitability of an investment or the performance of a division by comparing income with the operational assets used to generate that income. It is calculated in several ways, depending on the context:\n\n1. ROI = (Controllable profit / Total net assets) * 100\n2. ROI = Controllable profit / Capital employed * 100 for managers and ROI = Traceable profit / Capital employed * 100 for divisions\n3. ROI = Operating profit / Capital employed\n4. ROI = Net Profit / Net Assets\n5. ROI = Net profit / Capital employed\n\nThese formulas highlight that ROI can be expressed as a percentage and is used to determine the target profit in target costing. For example, Division A has an ROI of 15.08%, and Division B has an ROI of 17.72%. This metric is crucial for assessing the efficiency of investments and comparing the performance of different investments or divisions.\",6\n2275,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS: IMPLEMENTING THE BALANCED SCORECARD AND RESIDUAL INCOME APPROACHES\"\"\",\"\"\"Brace Co, an electronics company specializing in home audio equipment, is exploring the balanced scorecard approach and residual income (RI) for performance measurement and investment decisions. The case involves calculating ROI and RI for two divisions and discussing the implications for decision-making and goal congruence.\"\"\",3\n80,\"\"\"CUSTOMER RELATIONSHIP MANAGEMENT SYSTEM (CRM)\"\"\",\"A Customer Relationship Management System (CRM) records the relationship between the enterprise and its customers, managing interactions and data throughout the customer lifecycle.\",6\n1056,\"\"\"CAPITAL EMPLOYED\"\"\",\"\"\"Capital employed\"\" is the total amount of capital used for the acquisition of profits. It is equivalent to total assets less current liabilities or total equity plus long-term debt. This includes non-current assets, inventory, and trade receivables, minus trade payables.\",6\n1509,\"\"\"NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS\"\"\",\"Non-financial performance indicators are metrics used to assess various aspects of a company's performance that are not directly related to financial outcomes. These indicators encompass areas such as quality, customer satisfaction, employee engagement, and operational efficiency, which can lead to better long-term performance. They complement financial performance measures and help avoid excessive cost-cutting that may harm the business. Examples of non-financial performance indicators include customer satisfaction, employee turnover, operational efficiency, student transfer rates, late enrolments, exam pass rates, labor turnover, student complaints, and the average number of employees.\",6\n1177,\"\"\"ROI\"\"\",\"Return on Investment (ROI) is a performance measure used to evaluate the efficiency or profitability of an investment or to compare the efficiency of several different investments. It is calculated by dividing the net profit by the cost of the investment and is expressed as a percentage. Specifically, ROI can be calculated using the formula: (Net Profit / Operating Net Assets) * 100, or alternatively, Profit / Opening Investment (Net Book Value). This measure helps in assessing the profitability of an investment or division by comparing net profit to the capital employed.\",8\n1537,\"\"\"QUIZ: ROI VS. RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz compares the decision-making process using ROI and RI for a project with a projected ROI of 21.5%. It highlights the differences in acceptance criteria between the two measures.\"\"\",4\n1174,\"\"\"RESIDUAL INCOME (RI)\"\"\",\"Residual Income (RI) is the amount of income that an individual or company has after all expenses have been paid. It is calculated by subtracting the imputed interest charge from the net profit. RI serves as a measure of the profitability of an investment after accounting for the cost of capital. Specifically, it is determined by taking the divisional profit and deducting the imputed interest charge. For instance, Division A has a Residual Income of $2.552 million, while Division B has a Residual Income of $2.322 million. This metric focuses on wealth creation by deducting an imputed interest expense from the pre-tax profit.\",6\n2269,\"\"\"NET MARGIN\"\"\",\"\"\"Net margin is the percentage of revenue remaining after all operating expenses, interest, taxes, and preferred stock dividends have been deducted from a company's total revenue. It measures overall profitability.\"\"\",3\n1539,\"\"\"QUIZ: ROI AND RI FOR DIVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz examines the appraisal outcomes for two divisions using both ROI and RI, considering factors like depreciation and capital employed.\"\"\",3\n1959,\"\"\"ASSESSING DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT A MANUFACTURING COMPANY\"\"\",\"\"\"The Biscuits division (Division B) and the Cakes division (Division C) of a large manufacturing company are evaluated based on their ROI and residual income. Senior management has decided to recharge head office costs to the divisions, affecting their net profit and ROI calculations. The case involves calculating the expected annualized ROI and residual income for each division, discussing their performance, and considering the impact of a new machinery investment on Division B's ROI and residual income.\"\"\",4\n1184,\"\"\"RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"Residual Income (RI) is calculated as the net profit after deducting an imputed interest charge on the capital employed. It is used to assess the profitability of an investment or division, as well as the performance of divisions within a company. Residual income represents the income that remains after subtracting the imputed interest charge on capital employed from the controllable profit.\"\"\",6\n1055,\"\"\"RETURN ON CAPITAL EMPLOYED (ROCE)\"\"\",\"Return on Capital Employed (ROCE) is a financial metric used to measure the profitability and efficiency of a company's capital investments. It is calculated as the operating profit divided by the sum of equity and long-term liabilities, multiplied by 100. Alternatively, ROCE can also be expressed as the product of asset turnover and operating profit margin. Another way to calculate ROCE is by dividing profit before interest and tax by capital employed, then multiplying by 100. This metric provides insight into how well a company is generating profits from its capital and is a key indicator of financial performance.\",4\n70,\"\"\"CUSTOMER SERVICE\"\"\",\"Customer service involves assisting and supporting customers before, during, and after a purchase to ensure a positive experience and satisfaction. It encompasses the assistance and advice provided by a company to those who buy or use its products or services. Customer service is vital in service industries and also critical in manufacturing industries.\",4\n1180,\"\"\"PROPOSAL 2\"\"\",\"\"\"Proposal 2 is not acceptable to the company. The return on existing assets is 13% ($0.3m/$2.3m), which is greater than the cost of capital and hence should not be disposed of. However, divisional ROI rises, which could lead to the divisional manager accepting it. Residual income decreases if Proposal 2 is adopted, leading to goal-congruent decisions.\"\"\",2\n1176,\"\"\"QUIZ: ROI AND RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the current ROI and residual income for Division X and showing how they would change under two proposals.\"\"\",2\n1541,\"\"\"QUIZ: ROI CALCULATION FOR DAMON CO\u2019S DIVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the ROI for one of Damon Co\u2019s divisions based on provided financial information, including revenue, variable costs, fixed operating costs, apportioned head office costs, interest charges, and tax.\"\"\",2\n1172,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF ROI\"\"\",\"\"\"Advantages of ROI include ease of comparison between divisions, focus on scarce capital resources, encouragement of reduction in non-essential investment, and easily understood percentages.\"\"\",1\n1186,\"\"\"CONTROLLABLE PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Controllable profit is the profit within the manager's control.\"\"\",3\n72,\"\"\"SALES GROWTH\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales growth\"\" refers to the increase in sales over a specific period, often measured as a percentage increase from one period to the next. In a specific example, overall sales growth was calculated as $238,500/$200,000, resulting in a +19.25% increase. However, it is noted that sales in the female hairdressing sector have fallen by 15%, calculated as ($200,000 - $170,000)/$200,000.\",3\n1173,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF ROI\"\"\",\"\"\"Disadvantages of ROI include the risk of dysfunctional decision-making, subjective definition of capital employed, potential increase in ROI over time due to depreciation, and risk of window-dressing.\"\"\",1\n1956,\"\"\"EVALUATING PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT WELCO\"\"\",,3\n1909,\"\"\"OPERATING PROFIT MARGIN\"\"\",\"The \"\"Operating Profit Margin\"\" is calculated as (Operating profit / Revenue) * 100. This metric indicates the percentage of revenue that remains after covering operating expenses. Recently, there has been a decline in the operating profit margin from 20.8% to 20.0%, attributed to an increase in costs. When considering standard room rates per night, which reflect the impact of discounts and increased costs, the margin falls further from 18.9% to 17.6%.\",5\n1054,\"\"\"RETURN ON EQUITY (ROE)\"\"\",\"Return on equity (ROE) is a financial metric used to measure the profitability of a company in relation to its equity. It is calculated as Profit after tax divided by the sum of Share capital and reserves, multiplied by 100. Alternatively, ROE can also be expressed as Profit before or after tax divided by Equity. This ratio provides insight into how effectively a company is using its equity to generate profits.\",2\n1175,\"\"\"IMPUTED INTEREST\"\"\",\"\"\"Imputed interest\"\" is a notional interest charge calculated on the capital employed by the head office. It is determined by multiplying the capital employed by the interest rate. This imputed interest is used in the calculation of residual income.\",2\n1065,\"\"\"ASSET TURNOVER RATIO\"\"\",\"The \"\"Asset Turnover Ratio\"\" is calculated as Revenue divided by Capital Employed. This ratio measures how efficiently a company uses its assets to generate sales.\",3\n1967,\"\"\"NON-CURRENT ASSETS\"\"\",\"\"\"Non-current assets are long-term investments or assets that are not expected to be converted into cash within a year, such as property, plant, and equipment.\"\"\",1\n1968,\"\"\"INVENTORY AND TRADE RECEIVABLES\"\"\",\"\"\"Inventory and trade receivables represent the value of goods available for sale and the amounts owed to the company by customers for goods or services delivered.\"\"\",1\n1969,\"\"\"TRADE PAYABLES\"\"\",\"\"\"Trade payables are amounts a company owes to suppliers for items or services purchased on credit.\"\"\",1\n69,\"\"\"CUSTOMER DATA\"\"\",\"\"\"Customer data includes any information related to customers, such as contact details, purchase history, preferences, and feedback.\"\"\",1\n68,\"\"\"CUSTOMER INTERACTIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"Customer interactions refer to the various ways in which a business engages with its customers, including communication through emails, phone calls, social media, and in-person meetings.\"\"\",1\n71,\"\"\"CUSTOMER RETENTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Customer retention refers to the strategies and actions a business takes to keep its existing customers and reduce customer churn.\"\"\",1\n1958,\"\"\"GEARBOX DIVISION CAPITAL EQUIPMENT INVESTMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The Gearbox division is considering investing in capital equipment costing $2.7m with an expected useful economic life of 50 years and no resale value. The forecast return on the initial investment is 15% per year before depreciation, and the division's cost of capital is 7%. The expected annual residual income of the initial investment is calculated to be $162,000.\"\"\",1\n1971,\"\"\"INVESTMENT DECISION BASED ON RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"Investment decisions based on residual income consider whether the residual income generated by a project exceeds the cost of capital, guiding whether to proceed with the investment.\"\"\",2\n1510,\"\"\"QUIZ ON NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying appropriate non-financial performance indicators to monitor and improve the performance of a department within Smithson Co. The correct answers are A (Percentage of quotations found to contain errors when checked) and C (Actual staff employed as a percentage of the quota for the department).\"\"\",1\n1514,\"\"\"QUIZ ON INCENTIVE SCHEME FOR PRODUCT QUALITY\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying the most appropriate basis for an incentive scheme aimed at improving product quality at Yobo Co. The correct answer is C (Levels of rework).\"\"\",1\n1515,\"\"\"QUIZ ON MEASURE FOR IMPROVING CUSTOMER SATISFACTION\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying the most appropriate measure for an incentive scheme aimed at improving customer satisfaction at Cawlin Co. The correct answer is B (A decrease in the number of calls referred to a supervisor).\"\"\",1\n1516,\"\"\"QUIZ ON PERFORMANCE MEASURE FOR PRODUCT QUALITY\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying the most appropriate performance measure for an incentive scheme aimed at improving product quality at Lukers Co. The correct answer is C (Volume of products returned by customers).\"\"\",1\n1970,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE-RELATED BONUS\"\"\",\"\"\"A performance-related bonus is an additional compensation paid to managers based on the achievement of specific performance metrics, such as ROI.\"\"\",1\n1304,\"\"\"PLASTICS DIVISION\u2019S RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz question asks what is the plastic division\u2019s residual income given the following data: The plastics division of Ladmar has just reported a divisional return on capital employed of 30% for the last 12 months. The capital employed in the plastics division is $1,200,000. The company\u2019s overall return on capital employed is 18%, and the overall cost of capital is 14%. The plastics division\u2019s cost of capital is 13%. The correct answer is C. The divisional profit is $1.2m * 30% = $360,000. Imputed interest is $1.2m * 13% = $156,000. Therefore, residual income = $360,000 \u2212 $156,000 = $204,000.\"\"\",1\n1178,\"\"\"RI\"\"\",\"\"\"RI (Residual Income) is calculated as the net operating income minus the product of the investment cost and the cost of capital. It is used to measure the absolute amount of profit generated above the required return.\"\"\",5\n1191,\"\"\"ROI AND RESIDUAL INCOME CALCULATION\"\"\",,1\n1182,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"Residual income overcomes some of the problems associated with ROI, such as dysfunctional behavior and holding on to old assets. It can be linked to net present value, reflecting the best way to make investment decisions. A risk-adjusted cost of capital can reflect different risk positions of different divisions.\"\"\",1\n1961,\"\"\"COST OF CAPITAL\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost of capital\"\" is the rate of return required by a company to justify an investment. It represents the opportunity cost of using capital resources for a specific purpose. Additionally, it serves as the rate of return required to make a capital investment project worthwhile and is often used as a benchmark for evaluating investment decisions.\",2\n1086,\"\"\"NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"Non-financial performance assessment involves evaluating aspects of a business that are not directly related to financial metrics, such as customer satisfaction, service quality, and employee performance.\"\"\",2\n1183,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"Residual income has several disadvantages, including the definition of capital employed, the effect of depreciation, window dressing, and the challenge of comparing divisions of different sizes. It is also less easily understood than a percentage.\"\"\",1\n1908,\"\"\"OPERATING COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"There is no detail about Best Night Co's operating costs, for example, the split between fixed and variable costs. However, in an increasingly competitive market, cost control is likely to be very important. As such, the $3m (3.3%) increase in operating costs between 20X6 and 20X7 is potentially a cause for concern, and the reasons for the increase should be investigated further.\"\"\",1\n1910,\"\"\"ROCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Return on Capital Employed (ROCE) has fallen slightly from 62% ($24.2m/$39.1m) to 60.5% ($23.9m/$39.5m). This suggests that the value which Best Night Co is generating from its assets is falling.\"\"\",1\n1179,\"\"\"PROPOSAL 1\"\"\",\"\"\"Proposal 1 offers a 15% return ($0.15m/$1m), which is greater than the cost of capital. However, it leads to a decrease in divisional ROI, which could result in the divisional manager rejecting it. Residual income increases if Proposal 1 is adopted, leading to goal-congruent decisions.\"\"\",1\n1181,\"\"\"QUIZ: RESIDUAL INCOME\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves evaluating the performance of divisional managers using residual income. It includes scenarios where managers must decide on investment projects based on residual income calculations.\"\"\",1\n1960,\"\"\"HEAD OFFICE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Head office costs refer to the expenses incurred by the central administrative functions of a company. These costs are often recharged to individual divisions or departments to reflect their share of the overall administrative burden.\"\"\",1\n1546,\"\"\"NET PROFIT\"\"\",\"Net profit is the amount of income left after all expenses, including taxes, interest, and head office costs, have been deducted from total revenue. In the year 20X0, net profit was calculated as $78,000 out of $200,000, resulting in a net profit margin of 39%. In the year 20X1, net profit was $80,000 out of $238,500, resulting in a net profit margin of 33.5%.\",2\n1087,\"\"\"TRAINING FOR CUSTOMER SERVICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Training to ensure staff understand the importance of customer service. It helps improve performance in customer service.\"\"\",1\n1088,\"\"\"INCENTIVES FOR CUSTOMER SERVICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Incentives to staff to reward improvements in customer service, such as 'employee of the month' rewards and prizes for good performance.\"\"\",1\n1089,\"\"\"TARGET SETTING IN QUALITATIVE AREAS\"\"\",\"\"\"Target setting in qualitative areas\"\" involves establishing goals in non-financial aspects of the business, such as customer satisfaction and service quality. This process can be complicated due to the subjective nature of qualitative metrics and the challenges associated with non-financial performance measurement.\",3\n1093,\"\"\"DIFFICULTIES OF SETTING TARGETS FOR QUALITATIVE AREAS\"\"\",\"\"\"Challenges in setting targets for qualitative areas include identifying drivers of improved performance, measuring qualitative factors, staff behavior in response to targets, and setting the appropriate level of difficulty for targets.\"\"\",2\n2032,\"\"\"GROSS MARGIN\"\"\",\"Gross margin is the difference between sales revenue and the cost of goods sold, expressed as a percentage of sales revenue. It indicates the efficiency of a company in managing its production costs. For instance, the gross margin overall was calculated as $106,000/$200,000 or 53% in 20X0 and $112,500/$238,500 or 47.2% in 20X1. This metric can also be analyzed between female and male clients.\",2\n1066,\"\"\"ANALYSIS OF RETURN ON CAPITAL EMPLOYED\"\"\",\"\"\"Return on capital employed ratio (ROCE) is the product of the operating profit margin and the asset turnover. ROCE = Operating profit margin * Asset turnover. This relationship can provide insights into the ROCE for a particular business and help identify the underlying causes of a decline in ROCE.\"\"\",1\n2268,\"\"\"OVERHEAD CONTROL\"\"\",\"\"\"Overhead control involves managing and reducing indirect costs associated with running a business, such as administrative expenses, rent, and utilities. Effective overhead control can improve profitability.\"\"\",1\n1092,\"\"\"QUALITATIVE AREAS OF PERFORMANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"The most critical qualitative areas of performance include quality of product or service, customer satisfaction, delivery, and after-sales service.\"\"\",1\n1094,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF CALL CENTRE\"\"\",\"\"\"A call centre introduced a target of two minutes per call to increase the number of calls handled, but staff hung up on customers after two minutes to avoid a variance.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n190,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI)\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing involves determining the